  "reasoning": "For Problem 1, we analyze the functional equation f(x+y^2) = f(x) + |y f(y)|. Setting y=1 gives f(x+1) = f(x) + |f(1)|, so f(x+1) - f(x) = |f(1)|, a constant. Let c = |f(1)|. Setting x=0, y=1 gives f(1) = f(0) + c, so c = f(1) - f(0). Also, setting x=0, y=2 gives f(4) = f(0) + 2|f(2)|. Using the doubling property from setting x=y^2, we get f(2t) = 2f(t) - f(0) for t≥0. With t=2, f(4) = 2f(2) - f(0). Equating gives f(2) - f(0) = |f(2)|. Combining with f(2) = f(1) + c = f(0) + 2c, we get 2c = |f(0)+2c|. Let d = f(0). From c = |d+c|, we derive d(d+2c)=0. If d = -2c, then from 2c = |d+2c| we get 2c = 0, so c=0 and d=0. Thus f(0)=0 always, so k = f(0) + 4 = 4.\n\nFor Problem 2, we want the maximum number of distinct circles each passing through at least 4 of 7 points. To maximize, circles should contain exactly 4 points, and no two circles share three points (else they coincide). This reduces to finding the maximum number of 4-element subsets of a 7-element set with pairwise intersection at most 2. The maximum is 7, achieved by taking complements of the lines in the Fano plane (e.g., quadruples {4,5,6,7}, {2,3,6,7}, {2,3,4,5}, {1,3,5,7}, {1,3,4,6}, {1,2,5,6}, {1,2,4,7}). A geometric realization exists, yielding 7 distinct circles.",
